<div class="comment"><div class="commtext c00">Per the Bash `history` manpage:<p><pre><code>    int history_write_timestamps
       If non-zero, timestamps are written to the history file, so they can be preserved between sessions.  The default value is 0, [...]
</code></pre>
So this isn&#x27;t true by default on many machines unless it is explicitly turned on. Once you do have it on, of course, then I agree.</div><div class="reply"><p><font size="1"><u><a href="reply?id=44370044&amp;goto=item%3Fid%3D44364874%2344370044" rel="nofollow">reply</a></u></font></div></div></td></tr>
