<div class="comment"><div class="commtext c00">I have several use-cases &#x2F; problems I solve with my prompt:<p>- See current git branch (to not mistakenly work or commit into the wrong branch)<p>- See git has changes (to stash them before switching branches)<p>- See the current language&#x2F;engine version (like go v1.24.2, because i use tools like gvm, sdk, nvm or rustup to switch version in projects and i want feedback that i have the correct&#x2F;expected language version enabled)<p>- See that i am on my local or a remote machine and k8s context<p>That&#x27;s mostly it. Of course, I can do this by writing my own prompt, but I found out that Starship does this for me, basically out of the box, on any machine and terminal, in a very nice-looking way. Also, I am not a fan of fancy-looking prompts, so visually, Starship fits best for me.</div><div class="reply"><p><font size="1"><u><a href="reply?id=44371140&amp;goto=item%3Fid%3D44364874%2344371140" rel="nofollow">reply</a></u></font></div></div></td></tr>
